Playbook three — a runaway process pinning the CPU.

The symptoms: the load average is climbing, the fans are spinning up, and the whole system feels unresponsive. Something is eating all the CPU. Let's find it and deal with it.

Step one, find the culprit. Run top, which sorts by CPU usage by default, or press capital-P to be sure; htop gives you a nicer interactive view of the same thing. For a quick scriptable snapshot, ps dash-e-o with pid, user, percent-cpu, and comm, sorted by percent-cpu descending, and take the top few. Now you've got a PID.

Step two, and this is the interesting part, figure out what the process is actually doing. This is where strace shines. Run sudo strace dash-p, then the PID, and you'll see, live, every system call the process is making. Or strace dash-c dash-p for a summarized count after a few seconds. A process that's spinning in a tight syscall loop, say, opening the same file over and over, will make the bug obvious immediately. You can also read slash-proc-slash-the-pid-slash-cmdline to see its full command line.

Step three, take control, and escalate gently rather than reaching straight for the kill. First option: sudo renice plus-ten dash-p, the PID, which lowers its priority; that doesn't kill it, it just tells the scheduler to give everyone else a turn, which we covered in module five. Second: you can pause it entirely with kill dash-STOP, inspect the system while it's frozen, and then resume it with kill dash-CONT. And only if you need to, kill it, escalating from a polite SIGTERM, waiting a few seconds, and then a forceful dash-nine if it's still alive.

Step four, the frustrating case: what if you can't kill it, even with dash-nine? If the process is in the capital-D state, uninterruptible sleep, it's blocked deep in the kernel, usually waiting on disk or on a hung network filesystem, and, as we saw in module five, it simply cannot be killed by any signal. Your only options are to wait for the underlying I/O to finally complete, to fix the root cause, like unmounting a wedged NFS share, or, in the worst case, to reboot.
